# Jobs

Backgrounding and reclaiming work, mostly shared across @shell/bash and
@shell/zsh (fish and nu differ ‚Äî noted below). For sessions that must outlive a
disconnect, prefer a @tmux/session over `nohup`. Signals here pair with
@tools/* that send them.

## Job control ‚Äî bash / zsh

| Action | Command |
|--------|---------|
| run in background | `cmd &` |
| suspend the foreground job | `Ctrl-Z` (sends `SIGTSTP`) |
| list jobs | `jobs -l` |
| resume in background | `bg %1` |
| bring to foreground | `fg %1` |
| kill a job | `kill %1` |
| detach from shell (survive logout) | `disown %1` or `disown -h %1` |

`%1` is job number 1; `%%` is the most recent; `%-` the one before. A job
keeps the shell as parent until you `disown` it.

## Surviving a logout

| Tool | Use when |
|------|----------|
| `nohup cmd &` | one-shot: ignore `SIGHUP`, log to `nohup.out` |
| `setsid cmd` | start in a new session, fully detached |
| `disown -h %1` | already running ‚Äî shield it from `SIGHUP` |
| @tmux/session | interactive: reattach later, see output, multiple panes |

For anything you might want to *watch again*, a tmux session beats `nohup` ‚Äî
you keep a live terminal, not just a log file.

## Signals worth knowing

| Signal | Default effect | Send with |
|--------|----------------|-----------|
| `TERM` (15) | polite stop (catchable) | `kill PID` |
| `INT` (2) | interrupt | `Ctrl-C` |
| `HUP` (1) | hangup (terminal closed) | `kill -HUP` |
| `KILL` (9) | unconditional, uncatchable | `kill -9` (last resort) |
| `STOP` / `CONT` | pause / resume | `kill -STOP` / `kill -CONT` |

Reach for `KILL` only after `TERM` fails ‚Äî it gives the process no chance to
clean up temp files or flush buffers.

## fish and nu

- **fish**: `cmd &`, `jobs`, `fg`/`bg`, `disown` all work; there is no `Ctrl-Z`
  `bg` reflex difference worth noting.
- **nu**: backgrounding is intentionally limited ‚Äî run long jobs under a
  @tmux/session or `job spawn { ... }` for the built-in job list. nu favors a
  multiplexer over shell job control.
